AB  - The author's stance against anti-Semitism is somewhat counterbalanced, however, by assertions of biological determinism and racialist science. Zola claims that certain ethnic groups in this case, the Jews-have differently shaped skulls, reflecting at least in part the social Darwinist discourse of his day. This complicated response to the Jewish question is also at the core of American naturalist fiction. Donald Pizers seminal study Naturalism and the Jews (2008) examines the nativist representation of Jewish stereotypes in the work of Willa Cather, Theodore Dreiser, Hamlin Garland, Edith Wharton, and others. These authors, whose writings represent a wide range of regional settings, have become part of the naturalist canon (along with the literature of Kate Chopin, Stephen Crane, and Rebecca Harding Davis, among others). This "canonical" naturalism, Pizer argues, is identified with anti-Semitic rhetoric; specifically, he examines a prevailing negative attitude, in turn-of-the-century America, toward Jews living primarily in cities, and he shows how the language of naturalist novelists can perpetuate this racist ideology. Furthermore, Pizer looks particularly at the latter by giving attention to depictions of the Jew as an animal. While his work considers major naturalist authors, it does not extend to some of the period's less canonical voices.
